t assumptions ofthe authors, it contends that the precarious day-to-day existence of the three protagonists -- Yombo Melick, Dick Melick, and Quamino Buccau (Smock) -- provides revealing evidence about the various elements of "slave manhood" that gave real meaning to their oppressed lives. Kenneth E. Marshall is Assistant Professor of History at the State University of New York at Oswego.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAllinson, William J., -- 1810-1874. -- Memoir of Quamino Buccau, a pious Methodist. 0aBuccau, Quamino, -- 1762-1850?. 0aEnslaved personszNew JerseyvBiography. 0aMelick, Dick, -- b. ca. 1749. 0aMelick, Yombo, -- b. ca. 1739. 0aMellick, Andrew D., -- 1844-1895. -- Story of an old Farm. 0aSlavery -- New Jersey -- History. 0aSlavery in literature. 0aSlaveryzNew JerseyxHistory. 0aSlaves -- New Jersey -- Biography. 4aAfrican Studies. 4aModern History. 4aWomen's & Gender Studies. 7aHISTORY / United States / Revolutionary Period (1775-1800).2bisacsh  aAfrican History.  aBondpeople.  aCentral New Jersey.  aEnslaved Peoples.  aGender.  aRacial Oppression.  aSlave Manhood.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978158046740740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781580467407423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781580467407/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles